04769nam a22006495i 9780292762213DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211975txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927622137 a10.7560/7201212doi  a(DE-B1597)588555  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHM136b.A23 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a301.15/5  aMS 44502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123703:1 aAdams, Richard Newbold, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnergy and Structure :bA Theory of Social Power /cRichard Newbold Adams. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1975  a1 online resource (372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART ONE. THE NATURE OF POWER -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Basic Elements -- t3. Additional Considerations -- t4. The Variety of Operating Units -- t5. Power Domains and Levels -- tPART TWO. ENERGETIC AND MENTALISTIC STRUCTURES -- t6. A Note on Structure, Mind and Matter, and Culture -- t7. The Energetic -- t8. The Mentalistic -- tPART THREE. A MODEL OF THE EVOLUTION OF POWER -- t9. The Framework -- t10. Levels of Integration -- t11. Replicative Processes -- t12. Social Power and the Future -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAll social structures are essentially power structures dependent on energy. The concept of power and the role of energy in social organization are crucial and timely concerns, especially in light of the current apprehension about future energy resources. In Energy and Structure, Richard N. Adams argues that social power affects humanity's approach to ecological, economic, and political problems, directing people to seek solutions that are often deceptively shortsighted. Adams, an anthropologist, proposes that social power is directly derived from control over energy processes. He identifies how power and mentalistic structures constitute fundamental determinants that shape the lives of people at all stages of cultural development, forcing them to accept alternatives often far removed from their desires. His central thesis is that the amount of power in any system varies with the amount of control exercised over the environment and that increasing power and control lead to increasing centralization of decision-making, social marginalization, and environmental despoliation. Thus the more highly developed societies, by virtue of their greater controls, are responsible for the greater ultimate subordination and destruction of human potential, as humanity combines technological advances with a growing inability to exercise good judgment with respect to our own survival. Energy and Structure begins with an examination of the basic theory of social power—what it is and how it works. Adams defines and differentiates between the concepts of power and control, authority and legitimacy, power domains and levels. He then examines the underlying metatheory of energetic and mentalistic structures and provides an analytic model of the evolution of power, from the primitive band to modern nations. He predicts the emergence of supranational blocs and discusses other future possibilities. Throughout, his theoretical points are solidly supported by examples drawn from a wide range of cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aSocial structure. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72012140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292762213423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292762213/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  